{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18377"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7461"},{"type":"tags","id":"7465"},{"type":"tags","id":"7471"},{"type":"tags","id":"10241"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25727"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the talonavicular ligament?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supports the medial longitudinal arch","Facilitates plantar flexion of the foot","Prevents excessive dorsiflexion of the foot","Stabilises the lateral longitudinal arch","Connects the calcaneus to the cuboid bone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe talonavicular ligament is an important structure in the foot that primarily functions to \u003Cstrong\u003Esupport the medial longitudinal arch\u003C/strong\u003E. This ligament helps maintain the alignment and stability of the foot during weight-bearing activities, such as walking or standing. Injury or dysfunction in this ligament can result in pain and flattening of the arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExplanation of incorrect options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilising the lateral longitudinal arch\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary function of the talonavicular ligament. The lateral arch is supported by other structures, including the calcaneocuboid ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe talonavicular ligament does not \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent excessive dorsiflexion\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitate plantar flexion\u003C/strong\u003E of the foot. These movements are primarily controlled by the ankle joint and associated tendons and muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe talonavicular ligament does not \u003Cstrong\u003Econnect the calcaneus to the cuboid bone\u003C/strong\u003E. This connection is made by the calcaneocuboid ligament, which is part of the lateral column of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The talonavicular ligament is a key stabiliser of the medial longitudinal arch of the foot.","It plays a crucial role in maintaining the alignment and function of the foot during weight-bearing activities."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T16:29:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T16:31:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},